<% provide(:title, 'Faro10 - Addressing Mental Health on campus') %>



<br>
<div class="row">
  <div class="col-md-5 col-md-offset-1">

    <h4>In a 2016 survey of students by the American College Health Association, over 50% of students surveyed reported feeling that things were hopeless,
      and 39% reported feeling so depressed that it was difficult to function during the past 12 months.  </h4>
  </div>

</div>
<hr>

<div class="row">
  <div class="col-md-6 col-md-offset-5">
    <h4>
      In addition, the Center for Collegiate Mental Health at Penn State, which annually reports on college students receiving mental health services,
      found that the number who have purposely injured themselves (for instance, by cutting themselves) rose steadily to almost 26 percentin the 2015-16 school year,
      from 21.8 percent in 2010-11. The same upward trend was true of those who seriously considered attempting suicide rising to 33.2 percent, up from 23.8 percent, over the same period.
      <br>
      While demand is increasing for treatment, University Counseling Centers  have limited resources and are unable to serve students who may require a
      higher level of mental health treatment services.
    </h4>
  </div>
</div>
<hr>
<div class="row">
  <div class="col-md-10 col-md-offset-1">
    <h1>Something has to change. Is your campus doing everything it can to better address the mental health challenges it faces?</h1>
  </div>
</div>
<hr>
